snippet.textDisplay:
Terrible musical arrangement. Mooralalaji is the main star. Ripping away the total folk feel instead of supplementing it is so "typical" of wanting to prove oneself attitude that goes on behind the scenes on Coke Studio. Also, isn't it simply vain of the music producer to put his name as the first in the credit and say "featuring" Mooralalaji?!
I was behind the scenes in Coke Studio 1 and also the artist coordinator for the Kabir Festival where I was in charge of Mooralalaji. Inspite of the brickbats Leslie Lewis received for season 1, I can say firsthand he did a far better job of preserving the integrity of a musical style. And Mooralalaji is beyond words. The man is singing of a woman surrendered in love through "Waari Jaun Re". Is there a bigger example of surrender? His devotion gave us goosebumps and made us come alive during the Kabir festival. Anyone who wants to touch the soul of folk music must simply go to the Kabir Festival that happens every year in January for free across 25 locations or so in Mumbai. It is then followed by the Malwa Yatra where you journey across the villages these folk artists come from and perform in their villages. The hospitality and soul of India is so vibrant there, it's as if at the core there is an India that is untouchable by consumerism or capitalism.
